Generalises iter-054's $\mathtt{basicOpenCover\_isAffineOpen}$ (single-index affine membership) to pairwise intersections. Used by iter-057+ Čech evaluation: each finite intersection of basic opens is itself affine, which is the inductive step for the Koszul alternating-sum argument (Stacks 03F7 / Hartshorne III.4.5 / Eisenbud Commutative Algebra §17 Koszul resolution).

\subsection{N-ary basic-open intersection helpers (iter-057)}

Iter-057 (this iteration) generalises iter-056's binary intersection helpers to the $n$-ary case: the intersection of $\mathtt{basicOpenCover}\,s\,a$ over a non-empty $\mathtt{Finset}\,s$. The Mathlib $\mathtt{cechComplexFunctor}$ at degree $n$ for a family $\mathcal U : \iota \to C$ assigns the value of the presheaf on the product of $\mathcal U(x_i)$ over $i : \mathtt{Fin}(n+1)$ for each $x : \mathtt{Fin}(n+1) \to \iota$. In the basic-open setting, this product (= intersection in $\mathtt{Opens}$) of $(n+1)$ basic-open cover members identifies with the basic open of the product of the $(n+1)$ generators in $\Gamma(C.\mathtt{left}, U)$. Iter-057 packages this $n$-ary identification via the $\mathtt{Finset.inf'}$ shape (non-empty Finset; $\mathtt{Fin}(n+1)$-indexed iInf reduces to this via $\mathtt{Finset.univ}$) so iter-058+ Čech-evaluation arguments can apply it directly through induction on $\mathtt{Finset.cons}$.

\textbf{Why $\mathtt{Finset.inf'}$ (not $\mathtt{iInf}$ on $\mathtt{Fin}(n+1)$)}: probe-confirmed cleaner inductive structure via $\mathtt{Finset.cons\_induction}$. Mathlib does not have a direct $\mathtt{Fin.iInf\_succ}$ decomposition lemma; the $\mathtt{iInf}$ form requires either subsingleton-tracking at the base case or fiddly motive manipulation. The $\mathtt{Finset.inf'}$ non-empty form admits a clean 6-line tactic body via $\mathtt{Finset.inf'\_cons}$ + $\mathtt{Finset.prod\_cons}$ + $\mathtt{Scheme.basicOpen\_mul}$.

\textbf{Mathlib name correction this iteration}: the spanning-set exactness lemma in $\mathtt{Mathlib/RingTheory/LocalProperties/Exactness.lean}$ is $\mathtt{exact\_of\_isLocalized\_span}$, NOT $\mathtt{exact\_of\_localized\_span}$ as iter-054/055/056 informal scoping claimed. The corrected reference is module-flavoured; the parallel ring-flavoured lemma is $\mathtt{injective\_of\_isLocalization\_of\_span\_eq\_top}$ (same file).

\begin{theorem}\leanok
[$N$-ary basic-open intersection equals basic open of finite product, iter-057]
  \label{thm:Scheme_basicOpenCover_finset_inf_eq_basicOpen_prod}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.basicOpenCover_finset_inf'_eq_basicOpen_prod}
  \uses{def:Scheme_basicOpenCover}
  Let $k$ be a field, $C : \Over\,(\Spec\,(\CommRingCat.\mathtt{of}\,k))$, $U$ an open of $C.\mathtt{left}$, $s \subseteq \Gamma(C.\mathtt{left}, U)$, $t : \mathtt{Finset}\,s$, and $h : t.\mathtt{Nonempty}$. Then
  \[
    t.\mathtt{inf'}\,h\,(\mathtt{basicOpenCover}\,s) \,=\, C.\mathtt{left}.\mathtt{basicOpen}\Big(\prod_{i \in t} (i.1 : \Gamma(C.\mathtt{left}, U))\Big).
  \]
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}\leanok
  Finset induction via $\mathtt{Finset.cons\_induction}$. The empty case is impossible by $h : t.\mathtt{Nonempty}$ (closed via $\mathtt{Finset.not\_nonempty\_empty}$). The cons case splits on whether the residual $t$ is empty or non-empty: in the empty residual case, the LHS reduces to a single $\mathtt{basicOpenCover}\,s\,a = C.\mathtt{left}.\mathtt{basicOpen}\,a.1$ (closed via $\mathtt{simp}\,[\mathtt{basicOpenCover}]$); in the non-empty residual case, decompose via $\mathtt{Finset.inf'\_cons}\,h_{ne}$ to get $\mathtt{basicOpenCover}\,s\,a \sqcap (t.\mathtt{inf'}\,h_{ne}\,(\mathtt{basicOpenCover}\,s))$, decompose the product via $\mathtt{Finset.prod\_cons}$ to $a.1 \cdot (\prod_{i \in t} i.1)$, apply the induction hypothesis $\mathtt{ih}\,h_{ne}$ to the residual, and finally a $\mathtt{change}$ + $\mathtt{rw}\,[\leftarrow \mathtt{Scheme.basicOpen\_mul}]$ unifies the two forms. Body: $\mathtt{by}\,\mathtt{classical};\,\mathtt{induction}\,t\,\mathtt{using}\,\mathtt{Finset.cons\_induction}$ followed by the case-split tactics. Plan-agent $\mathtt{lean\_run\_code}$ probe (iter-057 pass) confirms kernel-only axioms $[\propext, \Classical.\mathtt{choice}, \Quot.\mathtt{sound}]$.
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}\leanok
[$N$-ary basic-open intersection on affine is itself affine, iter-057]
